    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <dateline>
                    <date when="1818-02-08"> </date></dateline>
                      
                         <p>
                          Sunday Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1818<lb/>
                               <note>8</note><lb/>
                       
                          <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">Miss Baillie's</persName> letter will not<lb/> 
                          be quite intelligible to you <lb/>
                          my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">Aunt</persName> without a<lb/>
                          note from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Me</persName>.—You must<lb/> 
                          know that just after you<lb/> 
                          left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> there appeared<lb/> 
                          in some <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> paper a <choice> 
                          <orig>let-<lb/>
                          ter</orig>
                          <reg>letter</reg>
                          </choice>
                          taken from a <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#STK">Scotch</placeName> paper<lb/>
                          called the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Craft1">Craftsman</title> <choice> 
                          <orig>con-<lb/>
                          taining</orig>
                          <reg>containing</reg>
                          </choice>
                          a sort of critique<lb/> 
                          or comparision between the<lb/> 
                          novels of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">miss E</persName> and of the<lb/> 
                          <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">author</persName> of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Waver1">Waverly</title> &amp;c—I <del>was</del><lb/> 
                          believing as I always have<lb/> 
                          done that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Walter Scott</persName> if<lb/> 
                          not the sole author at<lb/> 
                       
                       <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page02.jpg"/>
                          least the directing soul of those<lb/> 
                          works, and being really<lb/>
                          fond of him &amp; grateful for<lb/> 
                          his kindness to me was<lb/> 
                          particularly vexed to see<lb/>
                          this insidious <choice> 
                          <orig>compari<lb/>
                          son</orig>
                          <reg>comparison</reg>
                          </choice>
                          instituted between us<lb/>
                          for in the course of the <choice> 
                          <orig>de-<lb/>
                          fence</orig>
                          <reg>defence</reg>
                          </choice>
                          of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">miss E</persName> which this<lb/> 
                          purported to be many things<lb/> 
                          were said about him in<lb/>
                          which I should be very sorry<lb/>
                          he could think that <choice> 
                          <orig>under<lb/>
                          hand</orig>
                          <reg>underhand</reg>
                          </choice>
                          or any way I had<lb/> 
                          any concern—I wrote to<lb/> 
                          my friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">Joanna</persName> <choice> 
                          <orig>express-<lb/>
                          ing</orig>
                          <reg>expressing</reg>
                          </choice>
                          these feelings—<lb/> </p>
                       
                       <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page03.jpg"/>
                          <p>
                          Now the first part of her<lb/> 
                          letter will be intelligence<lb/> 
                          but you will come to a story<lb/> 
                          about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GordA2" cert="medium">Sir Alex<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Gordon</persName> wh<hi rend="superscript">h</hi><lb/>
                          requires an explanatory<lb/> 
                          preface—<lb/> </p>
                
                          <p>
                          All <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> you know was <choice> 
                          <orig>talk<lb/>
                          ing</orig>
                          <reg>talking</reg>
                          </choice>
                          over the long canvassed<lb/> 
                          question Is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">W. Scott</persName> or not the<lb/> 
                          author of the 3 unclaimed<lb/>
                          novels? — Now one of the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiX2">Miss<lb/> 
                          Hamilton’s</persName> told <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet B</persName><lb/>
                          who told me the following<lb/>
                          anecdote.<lb/> </p>
                
                          <p>
                          That <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GordA2" cert="medium">Sir Alex Gordon</persName> had<lb/> 
                          declared to her his conviction<lb/> 
                          of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">W. Scott</persName> being the author<lb/> 
                          because before the <choice> 
                          <orig>publica<lb/>
                          tion</orig>
                          <reg>publication</reg>
                          </choice>
                          of <title ref="./Workography.xml#GuyMa1">Guy Mannering</title> he<lb/> 
                          the said <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GordA2">Sir Alex<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName> went<lb/>
                       
                       <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page04.jpg"/>
                          to one of his tenants houses<lb/>
                          where he met <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">W. Scott</persName> &amp; where<lb/> 
                          first such a scene passed as is<lb/> 
                          painted in <title ref="./Workography.xml#GuyMa1">Guy Mannering</title><lb/>
                          at the funeral of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeX2">Steeney</persName> -<lb/> 
                          The said <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GordA2">Sir Alex<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName> further<lb/>
                          declared that when he again<lb/>
                          met <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Walter Scott</persName> after the <choice> 
                          <orig>pub<lb/>
                          lication</orig>
                          <reg>publication</reg>
                          </choice>
                          of <title ref="./Workography.xml#GuyMa1">Guy Mannering</title><lb/>
                          &amp; reminded him or was<lb/> 
                          going to remind him of<lb/> 
                          this circumstance <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Walter<lb/>
                          Scott</persName> put his finger on his<lb/> 
                          lips in token of silence<lb/> 
                          &amp; secrecy—<lb/> </p>
                
                          <p>
                          It appears you will see<lb/> 
                          that the knight would<lb/> 
                          have done better to be silent<lb/>
                          </p>
                
                         <closer> 
                           Y<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> affectionately<lb/> 
                          <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                        </closer>
                                
            </div>
